[]{#ch10lvl1sec89}Introduction {#introduction .title style="clear: both"}
------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

Nowadays, almost all organizations are trying to become data-driven.
Organizations collect data about sales, customer behavior, user
experience, inventory, clickstream, marketing activity, and more. As a
result, the data volume is huge and can\'t fit in a single computer.
There are also other attributes of big data such as velocity, variety,
and value. BI and data engineers should use different analytics
platforms that are able to process big volumes of data, often
unstructured or streaming in real time.

Another important trend in the industry is shifting to the cloud. There
are multiple leaders such as AWS, Google, and Azure, which offer cloud
infrastructure, high availability, and security of the data. The cloud
gives us a lot of advantages and also gives us more time to focus on
data processing and analysis.

Tableau supports more than 40 different data sources. There are
plenty[]{#id325437451 .indexterm} of data sources available for big data
ecosystems, as follows:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   [**Cloud Data Platforms**]{.strong}: Snowflake, Amazon Redshift, AWS
    Spectrum, Amazon Athena, Google BigQuery, and so on
-   [**Hadoop**]{.strong}: Cloudera, Hortonworks, Hive, Presto, and so
    on
-   [**MPP databases**]{.strong}: Teradata, Oracle Exadata, HP Vertica,
    Exasol, SAP HANA, and many more
:::

In this chapter, we will learn how to connect[]{#id324855866 .indexterm}
the most popular[]{#id324855881 .indexterm} big data platforms, such as
Amazon Redshift, Snowflake, and Hadoop to Tableau. Moreover, we will
look into the data lake concept and will connect our raw data to Tableau
using Amazon Spectrum.

It is important to understand that the key element for working with
massive datasets in Tableau is good data engineering execution, to make
sure that all heavy lifting is performed by the big data systems.
Tableau will just render the query results.

 


[]{#ch10lvl1sec90}Connecting with Amazon Redshift {#connecting-with-amazon-redshift .title style="clear: both"}
-------------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

[**Amazon Web Services**]{.strong} ([**AWS**]{.strong}) completely
changed[]{#id325674355 .indexterm} the way that IT infrastructure is
deployed. It is available on demand and is cost-effective. Amazon
Redshift is one of the hundreds[]{#id325386993 .indexterm} of AWS
services and it is one of the most popular cloud data warehouses. It is
fast, secure, and petabyte-scale. Redshift combines[]{#id325386994
.indexterm} the following two important technologies:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   Columnar data store[]{#id326626106 .indexterm} or column-oriented
    database
-   [**Massively parallel processing**]{.strong} ([**MPP**]{.strong})
:::

You can learn more about MPP and column databases on the Internet. You
can find more information about Redshift at AWS\'s
documentation: [https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/index.html](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/index.html#lang/en_us){.ulink}

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec301}Getting ready {#getting-ready .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

Before we start, we need to create an AWS account or use an existing
one. AWS offers us a two month free trial, and then we can spin up the
smallest Redshift cluster and do important network settings to open
access from our local machine to Amazon Redshift. Finally, we will load
some sample data into Redshift from an S3 bucket, and then we will query
and connect Tableau Desktop.

In this section, we will go deep into data engineering design to show
you the main principles of working with big data, so that we can use the
strength of each tool. These patterns could be applicable to any other
big data platform.

#### []{#ch10lvl3sec44}Creating an IAM role {#creating-an-iam-role .title}

</div>

We should create an [**IAM**]{.strong} role to get access[]{#id325192728
.indexterm} to data for another AWS resource, such as Amazon S3 buckets
because our cluster needs some permissions to access the resources and
the data. You can learn more about IAM and permissions to access other
AWS resources
here: <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/copy-usage_notes-access-permissions.html>

Follow these steps to create an IAM role:

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  Go to **`IAM`** and choose **`Roles`**.
2.  Click **`Create Role`**.
3.  Under **`AWS services`**, choose **`Redshift`**.
4.  Under **`Select your use case`**, choose
    **`Redshift Customizable`**, and then click **`Next`**.
5.  Attach **`AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess`** and click **`Next`**.
6.  Type the role name, **`RedshiftS3Access`**, and click **`Create`**.
7.  Open the role that we just created and copy[]{#id325269178
    .indexterm} the [**Amazon Resource**]{.strong}[**Name**]{.strong}
    ([**ARN**]{.strong}):
:::

Let\'s view the results of the steps we carried out in the following
screenshot: 

::: {.mediaobject}
![](data:image/png;base64,)
:::

We will need this later in this chapter.

[]{#ch10lvl1sec92}Connecting a Redshift cluster {#connecting-a-redshift-cluster .title style="clear: both"}
-----------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

The cluster should be created by now, and we should test that we can
connect to the cluster from our local machine. The best way to do this
is to download[]{#id325192630 .indexterm} the SQL client and connect to
it using the JDBC driver. It is the common pattern for databases or
analytics tool connections. 

The cluster should be created and we should test that we can connect to
the cluster from our local machine. The best way to do this is to
download an SQL client and connect using the JDBC driver. It is the
common pattern for database or analytics tool connection.

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec307}How to do it... {#how-to-do-it .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

We will connect the Redshift cluster using the following steps:

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  Let\'s download the Redshift SQL client. There are many available
    clients. Some of them are free, while others aren\'t. We will
    download[]{#id325774248 .indexterm} the DBeaver SQL client. Go
    to <https://dbeaver.io/download/> and download the lastest available
    package for your OS from
    <https://www.sql-workbench.eu/downloads.html>. In my case, I will
    use macOS X (pkg installer + JRE).
2.  We will now install DBeaver and launch it. It will offer us the
    option to create a new database connection. We should use
    **`AWS Redshift`**. The connection window will ask us about
    **`Host`**, **`Database`**, **`Port`**, **`User`**, and
    **`Passwords`**. We should copy them from the AWS console under our
    cluster properties.
3.  By default, any resource in AWS is closed. We should adjust the
    security settings to allow access to the Redshift cluster from local
    machine. Among the **`AWS Services`**, find **`EC2`** and click on
    it.
4.  On the left sidebar, click on **`Security Groups`**.
5.  Edit your **`VPC group`**. In my case, I have only one default
    group. If you have more than one group, you can check for, the VPC
    group associated with your cluster.
:::

 

::: {.orderedlist}
6.  Click **`Edit inbound rules`** and add a new rule. From the
    **`Source`**, you can choose **`My IP`**. Let\'s take a look at the
    results, which are shown[]{#id325774375 .indexterm} in the following
    screenshot:
:::

::: {.mediaobject}
![](data:image/png;base64,)
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
7.  Now, we can go back to **`DBeaver`** and enter our credentials for a
    new Redshift database connection. We should copy these credentials
    from the AWS console under the Redshift properties, as shown in the
    following screenshot:
:::

::: {.mediaobject}
![](data:image/png;base64,)
:::

 

DBeaver will offer us the ability to download the Redshift JDBC driver.
We will accept it and install the driver.

As a result, we have now connected[]{#id325189422 .indexterm} to the
Amazon Redshift cluster, and our next step is to get the sample data.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec308}How it works... {#how-it-works .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

To connect any data platform, we should obtain a driver and adjust the
firewall. In our case, we\'ve got an Amazon Redshift native JDBC driver.
In addition, we had to use the SQL client to connect Redshift and query
it. We used open source DBeaver, which served well for our purpose and
works perfectly in real life.
:::

### []{#ch10lvl2sec314}How it works... {#how-it-works .title}

When Tableau Desktop establishes a live connection, it acts in the same
way as the SQL client. The difference is that Tableau Desktop will
generate an SQL query based on our Tableau Data Source and query
Redshift every time we have updated the Tableau View by dragging and
dropping the new object or changing filters. 



[]{#ch10lvl1sec95}Creating a Tableau report {#creating-a-tableau-report .title style="clear: both"}
-------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

Let\'s ask questions with Tableau. For example, we want[]{#id326617925
.indexterm} to know the revenue in specific cities
(`UNITED KI5`{.literal}, `UNITED KI1`{.literal}) in December 1997.
Moreover, we want to order the result by revenue amount in descending
order.

 

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec315}How to do it... {#how-to-do-it .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  We are using a live connection, which means that each interaction
    with a report will generate an SQL query and we should wait. To
    avoid this, we will pause Tableau Auto Updates, as shown in the
    following screenshot:
:::

::: {.mediaobject}
![](9_files/efcfc7da-aabe-4f57-b877-c52ed50cb158.png)
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
2.  Now, we can craft our report by dragging and
    dropping **`Dimensions`** and **`Measures`** to the canvas, as
    follows:
:::

 

::: {.orderedlist}
3.  You should add the following filters:
:::

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   **`C City`**: `UNITED KI1`{.literal} or `UNITED KI5`{.literal}
-   **`S City`**: `UNITED KI1`{.literal} or `UNITED KI5`{.literal}
-   **`D YEAR`**: `Dec1997`{.literal}
:::

Moreover, we should convert **`D Year`** into discrete and sort by
**`Revenue`**.

::: {.orderedlist}
4.  We should unpause auto updates[]{#id325192728 .indexterm} and run
    our query. It takes \~18 seconds for my cluster. If we missed the
    time, we can log in to the **`AWS Console`** and navigate to the
    **`Redshift cluster`** \| **`Queries Tab`** and see all executed
    queries, their time, and plan. You might see that, in the case of
    Tableau, we don\'t have actual queries; instead, we have something
    like **`fetch 10000 in SQL_CUR7`**. Tableau is using cursors and we
    can run the following query to see queries for currently active
    cursors:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
SELECT
   usr.usename AS username
  , min(cur.starttime) AS start_time
  , DATEDIFF(second, min(cur.starttime), getdate()) AS run_time
  , min(cur.row_count) AS row_count
  , min(cur.fetched_rows) AS fetched_rows
  , listagg(util_text.text)
    WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY sequence) AS query
FROM STV_ACTIVE_CURSORS cur
  JOIN stl_utilitytext util_text
    ON cur.pid = util_text.pid AND cur.xid = util_text.xid
  JOIN pg_user usr
    ON usr.usesysid = cur.userid
GROUP BY usr.usename, util_text.xid;
```
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
5.  Let\'s run one more system query that will help us to identify the
    size of tables we are using in our Tableau data source, as follows:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
select stv_tbl_perm.name as table, count(*) as mb from stv_blocklist, stv_tbl_perm
where stv_blocklist.tbl = stv_tbl_perm.id
and stv_blocklist.slice = stv_tbl_perm.slice and stv_tbl_perm.name in ('lineorder','part','dwdate','supplier')
group by stv_tbl_perm.name
order by 1 asc;
```
:::

We can notice the size of the tables:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   `lineorder`{.literal}=`34311mb`{.literal}
-   `part`{.literal}=`92mb`{.literal}
-   `dwdate`{.literal}=`80mb`{.literal}
-   `supplier`{.literal}=`76mb`{.literal}
:::

Finally, we can tune our cluster[]{#id325272413 .indexterm} to improve
the performance of the queries.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec316}How it works... {#how-it-works .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

We\'ve built a new report and analyzed the SQL query that was generated
by Tableau Desktop. In addition, we measured the performance and size of
the tables.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}

<div>

[]{#ch10lvl1sec96}Tuning Redshift for efficient Tableau performance {#tuning-redshift-for-efficient-tableau-performance .title style="clear: both"}
-------------------------------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

Every big data platform has special settings[]{#id325192645 .indexterm}
for tuning. For example, in our case, Redshift we will focus on the
following three options:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   Sort keys
-   Dist keys
-   Compression
:::

You can learn more about Redshift[]{#id325192614 .indexterm} tuning
here:

<https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/big-data/top-10-performance-tuning-techniques-for-amazon-redshift/>

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec318}How to do it\... {#how-to-do-it... .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

We will adjust our tables to get the maximum from Redshift in terms of a
place for computing, and, allow Tableau to efficiently render the
results and visualize it as follows:

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  To choose the right sort key, we should evaluate our queries to find
    a date column that we are using for filters (the `WHERE`{.literal}
    condition in SQL). For our huge fact table, it is the
    `lo_orderdate`{.literal} column. For the remaining dimension tables,
    we will use their primary key as a sort key: `p_partkey`{.literal},
    `s_supkey`{.literal}, `d_datekey`{.literal}.
2.  Then, we will choose candidates for the sort key. The following are
    the three types of distribution available in Redshift:
:::

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   The key distribution
-   The all distribution
-   The even distribution
:::

You can learn more about Redshift[]{#id324944110 .indexterm}
distribution at the following URL:

<https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/c_best-practices-best-dist-key.html>

 

::: {.orderedlist}
3.  To find the best[]{#id324944103 .indexterm} distribution style, we
    need to analyze the SQL query that is generated by Tableau and
    executed by Redshift. We should use the preceding query to extract
    the SQL from the cursor. Then, we should look to the execution plan
    by running our query with the word `EXPLAIN`{.literal}, as follows:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
explain
SELECT "customer"."c_city" AS "c_city", "dwdate"."d_year" AS "d_year", "supplier"."s_city" AS "s_city",
SUM("lineorder"."lo_revenue") AS "sum_lo_revenue_ok" 
FROM "public"."lineorder" "lineorder" 
INNER JOIN "public"."customer" "customer" ON ("lineorder"."lo_custkey" = "customer"."c_custkey") 
INNER JOIN "public"."supplier" "supplier" ON ("lineorder"."lo_suppkey" = "supplier"."s_suppkey") 
INNER JOIN "public"."dwdate" "dwdate" ON ("lineorder"."lo_orderdate" = "dwdate"."d_datekey") 
WHERE (("customer"."c_city" IN ('UNITED KI1', 'UNITED KI5')) 
AND (("supplier"."s_city" IN ('UNITED KI1', 'UNITED KI5')) 
AND ("dwdate"."d_yearmonth" IN ('Dec1997'))))
GROUP BY 1, 2, 3
```
:::

We will get the plan as follows:

::: {.mediaobject}
![](data:image/png;base64,)
:::

I\'ve highlighted `BS_BCAST_INNER`{.literal}. It means that the inner
join was broadcasted across all slices. We should eliminate any
broadcast and distribution steps. You can learn[]{#id325272407
.indexterm} more about query patterns here:

<https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/t_evaluating_query_patterns.html>

In our case, we should look at the join between the fact table with 600
mln and dimension tables. Based on fairly small rows in the dimension
tables, we can distribute the dimension tables `SUPPLIER`{.literal},
`PART`{.literal}, and `DWDATE`{.literal} across all nodes. For the
`LINEORDER`{.literal} table, we will use `lo_custkey`{.literal} as a
distribution key and for the `CUSTOMER`{.literal} table, we will use
the `c_custkey`{.literal} as the distribution key.

::: {.orderedlist}
4.  Next, we should compress our data to make sure that we can reduce
    storage space, and also, reduce the size[]{#id325272454 .indexterm}
    of the data that is read from storage. It decreases I/O and improves
    query performance. By default, all data is uncompressed. You can
    learn[]{#id325272491 .indexterm} more about compression encodings
    here: <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/c_Compression_encodings.html>.
    We should use system tables in order to research the best
    compression encoding. Let\'s run the following query:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
select col, max(blocknum)
from stv_blocklist b, stv_tbl_perm p
where (b.tbl=p.id) and name ='lineorder'
and col < 17
group by name, col
order by col;
```
:::

It will show us the highest block number for each column in the
`LINEORDER`{.literal} table. Then, we can start to experiment with
different encoding types in order to find the best. In addition, we
should always analyze the table after changes in order to update table
statistics. However, in our case, we can simply execute the
`COPY`{.literal} command with the auto compression parameter.

::: {.orderedlist}
5.  Let\'s apply the changes to our tables and run the same report. Copy
    the queries from the
    `Create_Statementv2_Redshift.sql`{.literal}[** **]{.strong}file and
    run them.
6.  Then, we should reload data with autocompression. Run SQL from
    the `COPY`{.literal} data to `Redshiftv2.txt`{.literal} file. Don\'t
    forget to insert your ARN.
7.  Let\'s refresh our Tableau workbook and see the improvements.
    Moreover, we can check the query plan and see the changes. In my
    case, it took 8 seconds.
:::
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec319}How it works\... {#how-it-works... .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

As you can see, the secret of working with big volumes of data is in
good design patterns of the Data Platform. In the case of Redshift, we
analyze the data structure, volume, and query patterns, and then apply
the best practices of using sort keys, distribution styles, and
compression encoding. It is obvious that we are depending on query
patterns, and we can keep high performance for any queries. As a result,
we should be very careful with the preceding options.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec320}There\'s more... {#theres-more .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

It is important for cost-based optimization[]{#id325285857 .indexterm}
databases such as Redshift to keep table statistics up-to-date in case
of any changes or updates by using the `ANALYZE`{.literal} and
`VACUUM`{.literal} commands.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}

[]{#ch10lvl1sec97}Connecting to Amazon Redshift Spectrum {#connecting-to-amazon-redshift-spectrum .title style="clear: both"}
--------------------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

In this section, we will upgrade our Redshift data warehouse by enabling
Redshift Spectrum, which plays the role of a data lake and compliments
our data warehouse. It gives us a powerful and serverless architecture
and can handle a tremendous volume of data, which is true big data.

Amazon Spectrum extends Redshift data warehouse[]{#id325269177
.indexterm} out to the Exabytes website. You can get all the benefits of
open data formats and inexpensive storage, and we can easily scale out
to thousands of nodes. Another benefit is the cost; we pay only for
usage and storage using S3, which is fairly small in comparison with an
analytical data warehouse.

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec322}Getting ready {#getting-ready .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

 We should update our IAM roles for Redshift by adding the following
additional policies:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   **`AmazonS3FullAccess`**
-   **`AmazonAthenaFullAccess`**
-   **`AWSGlueConsoleFullAccess`**
:::

Spectrum will use the Glue or Athena data catalog. It is important to
have the data in the region as our Redshift cluster. That\'s why we are
going to use the `UNLOAD`{.literal} command: so that we have the data in
the same network with our Redshift. In real life, we can query data from
other VPC in the same region.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec323}How to do it... {#how-to-do-it .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  Let\'s create an S3 bucket for our data. Go to **`S3`** and click
    on **`Create new bucket`**. Type the name
    `cookbook-spectrum`{.literal}.
2.  Now, we can unload data into this bucket and run this command, as
    shown in the following code block:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
unload ('select * from lineorder')
to 's3://cookbook-spectrum/
iam_role 'arn:aws:iam::615381814665:role/RedshiftS3Access'
delimiter '\t'
```
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
3.  Let\'s create the external schema, as follows:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
create external schema datalake 
from data catalog 
database 'spectrumdb' 
iam_role 'arn:aws:iam::615381814665:role/RedshiftS3Access'
create external database if not exists;
```
:::

 

 

 

 

::: {.orderedlist}
4.  Let\'s create an external[]{#id324855874 .indexterm} table in this
    schema, as follows:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
create external table datalake.lineorder
(
  lo_orderkey INTEGER 
  ,lo_linenumber INTEGER
  ,lo_custkey INTEGER
  ,lo_partkey INTEGER
  ,lo_suppkey INTEGER
  ,lo_orderdate INTEGER
  ,lo_orderpriority VARCHAR(15)
  ,lo_shippriority VARCHAR(1)
  ,lo_quantity INTEGER 
  ,lo_extendedprice INTEGER
  ,lo_ordertotalprice INTEGER 
  ,lo_discount INTEGER 
  ,lo_revenue INTEGER
  ,lo_supplycost INTEGER 
  ,lo_tax INTEGER 
  ,lo_commitdate INTEGER
  ,lo_shipmode VARCHAR(10)
)
row format delimited
fields terminated by '\t'
stored as textfile
location 's3://cookbook-spectrum/
table properties ('numRows'='172000');
```
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
5.  We can test this table by running queries against it, such as
    `SELECT * FROM datalake.lineorder`{.literal}, or we can adjust our
    Tableau Data Source and use a Spectrum table instead of the initial
    one. However, it is better to tune the external[]{#id324944091
    .indexterm} table before use, otherwise Spectrum will scan the full
    table.
:::

 
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}

### []{#ch10lvl2sec324}How it works\... {#how-it-works... .title}

</div>

[]{#ch10lvl1sec98}Connecting to Snowflake {#connecting-to-snowflake .title style="clear: both"}
-----------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

Snowflake is the leading cloud data warehouse[]{#id325272503 .indexterm}
platform. Moreover, it is the first data warehouse that was created for
the cloud. In this section, we will launch a Snowflake instance and
connect to it with Tableau. Currently, Snowflake is available for AWS
and Azure. We are going to use the AWS version of Snowflake.

Snowflake has a multi-cluster shared[]{#id325272488 .indexterm}
architecture, and it separates storage and computes. This allows it
to easily scale up and down on the fly without any disruption.

Snowflake is an SQL data warehouse that supports structured and
semi-structured data, such as JSON, AVRO, or XML.

The Snowflake architecture consists of the following three layers:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   [**Cloud services**]{.strong}: This is a collection of services such
    as authentication, and so on
-   [**Query processing**]{.strong}: Snowflake executes queries using a
    virtual warehouse, for example, an MPP cluster with multiple compute
    nodes using Amazon EC2 or Azure virtual machines
-   [**Database storage**]{.strong}: Snowflake stores optimized data in
    Amazon S3 or Azure Blob Storage
:::

 

Let\'s take a look at the following diagram that depicts the preceding
mentioned layers:

::: {.mediaobject}
![](data:image/png;base64,)
:::

There is the same principle when we allow Snowflake to do the heavy
lifting and then, Tableau renders the results. As a result, we don\'t
need[]{#id325272413 .indexterm} to use Tableau extracts.

With a live connection, we should avoid a custom SQL data source because
often it is counterproductive, and could be run multiple times on the
dashboard. Tableau itself can generate much more efficient queries.

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec327}Getting ready {#getting-ready .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

We should start the free trial of Snowflake. We can choose either AWS or
Azure. In my case, I will use AWS. After that, we will launch the
cluster, and then, we can load sample data and connect the Tableau
Desktop using a built-in Snowflake connector.
:::

::: {.titlepage}

[]{#ch10lvl1sec101}Connecting big data {#connecting-big-data .title style="clear: both"}
--------------------------------------

:::

Now, we can try to query a bigger[]{#id324855872 .indexterm} dataset and
see how Tableau will work with big data. We shouldn\'t avoid Tableau
Extracts, because our data size is huge. This is the great thing about
the cloud. We can orchestrate with big data without loading it into our
machine.

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec334}How to do it... {#how-to-do-it .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  We can create a new data source and specify the following options:
    ::: {.itemizedlist}
    -   **`Warehouse`**: `COMPUTE_WH`{.literal}
    -   **`Database`**: `SNOWFLAKE_SAMPLE_DATA`{.literal}
    -   **`Schema`**: `TPCH_SF1000`{.literal}
    :::
:::

You can learn[]{#id326677621 .indexterm} more about the TPC sample

at <http://www.tpc.org/tpc_documents_current_versions/pdf/tpc-ds_v2.5.0.pdf>.

::: {.orderedlist}
2.  When we are choosing **`Warehouse`**, we are choosing to compute

3.  Build the data model, as shown in the following screenshot:
:::

::: {.mediaobject}
![](15_files/5bb27d81-c328-42a9-b504-d1bfc114e5bb.png)
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
4.  Let\'s answer the following business question: List the totals for
    the extended price, discounted extended price plus tax, average
    quantity, average discount, and average extended price, and group
    the result by **`Return Flag`** and **`Line Status`**. Using
    Tableau, we can drag and drop the following object. Do not forget to
    pause Auto Updates. In addition, we should[]{#id326676853
    .indexterm} create the following calculation fields:
    ::: {.itemizedlist}
    -   **`Extended Discounted Price`**:
        `[L Extendedprice]*(1-[L Discount])`{.literal}
    -   **`Extended Discounted Price with Tax`**:
        `[L Extendedprice]*(1-[L Discount])*(1+[L Tax])`{.literal}
    :::
:::

Here is the screenshot showing the end result:

::: {.mediaobject}
![](15_files/4e282d7a-7351-459a-8b23-61c96ba4fc4f.png)
:::

 

::: {.orderedlist}
5.  We can check with Snowflake GUI about the actual plan by going to
    **`History`** and finding our **`Query`**. Because we are using a
    live connection, Tableau generates a query and uses only one
    table, `LINEITEM`{.literal}, instead of the whole data model, which
    saves us time and money.
:::

on Snowflake sample data. In addition, we had to specify a Virtual

using custom SQL logic or want to use aggregate tables by materializing

[]{#ch10lvl1sec102}Accessing semi--structured data {#accessing-semistructured-data .title style="clear: both"}
--------------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

In the modern world, often we can meet[]{#id324944115 .indexterm}
unstructured data that is generating by machines, apps, sensors, and so
on. There are the following two main attributes of semi-structured data
that differ it from structure data:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   Semi-structured data can contain n-level hierarchies of nested
    information
-   Structured data always needs a defined schema before loading it.
    Semi-structured data doesn\'t need this, so as a result we can
    create the schema on the fly
:::

Despite the fact that Tableau supports direct connection to the JSON
format, we still have the same issue with big data, when we need more
compute resource than Tableau allows us to use and also, we can collect
data types such as Avro, ORC, Parquet, and XML.

Usually, we should parse unstructured data and write into the table. But
not with Snowflake; it has a special data type `VARIANT`{.literal} that
allows us to store semi-structured data. Moreover, we can easily parse
key-value pairs. You can run the following SQL and check how it looks:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
select * from "SNOWFLAKE_SAMPLE_DATA"."WEATHER"."WEATHER_14_TOTAL" limit 1
```
:::

Let\'s try to use the Snowflake sample database in order to see how it
looks. Unfortunately, Tableau can\'t parse `VARIANT`{.literal} data
type, which is why we should create the SQL for Tableau based on a
`VARIANT`{.literal} column.

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec337}How to do it... {#how-to-do-it .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

Let\'s create a Tableau workbook based on semi-structured data. At the
Snowflake sample database we have a table `HOURLY_16_TOTAL`{.literal}
with 392 mln rows and 322 GB. This dataset keeps the last four days of
hourly weather forecasts for 20,000+ cities.

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  Create a new Tableau data source[]{#id324855908 .indexterm} with a
    Snowflake connection:
    ::: {.itemizedlist}
    -   **`Warehouse`**: `COMPUTE_WH`{.literal}
    -   **`Database`**: `SNOWFLAKE_SAMPLE_DATA`{.literal}
    -   **`Schema`**: `WEATHER`{.literal}
    :::
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
2.  Drag and drop custom SQL element and use this query, that will parse
    the `VARIANT`{.literal} data type, as follows:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
select (V:main.temp_max - 273.15)::FLOAT * 1.8000 + 32.00 as temp_max_far,      (V:main.temp_min - 273.15)::FLOAT * 1.8000 + 32.00 as temp_min_far,
  cast(V:time as timestamp) time,
       V:city.coord.lat::FLOAT lat,
       V:city.coord.lon::FLOAT lon,
       v:city.name::VARCHAR,
       v:city.country::VARCHAR,
      v:city:id,
      V
```
:::

From
`"SNOWFLAKE_SAMPLE_DATA"."WEATHER"." HOURLY_16_TOTAL"`{.literal}  you
can use another table that is much smaller, such as
`DAILY_14_TOTAL`{.literal} (37 mln rows). In addition, you can always
specify `LIMIT`{.literal} at the end of the query in order to limit you
output.

 

::: {.orderedlist}
3.  Then we can build the dashboard in order to see the minimum
    temperature in Fahrenheit across the world, as follows:
:::

::: {.mediaobject}
![](16_files/5cfcf1b9-83da-4448-9d40-63b86578fea5.png)
:::

Tableau has special function pass-through functions that can send SQL
expressions to the database, without being interpreted by Tableau. In
our case with weather[]{#id325272420 .indexterm} data, we can create a
new calculated field `WIND SPEED`{.literal}:
`RAWSQL_REAL("v:wind.speed::float",[V])`{.literal} and it will add wind
speed to our dataset.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec338}How it works\... {#how-it-works... .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

Tableau on top of Snowflake is fast because it is utilizing Snowflake\'s
computing power and just renders the result in Tableau.

 
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec339}There\'s more... {#theres-more .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

According to the best practices, if our semi-structured data schema is
static, we can parse it and load it into the Snowflake tables. We can
use SQL queries from the Snowflake GUI or SnowSQL CLI, or we can use
the ELT tool such as Matillion ETL. You can learn[]{#id325272452
.indexterm} more about Snowflake and[]{#id325272489 .indexterm}
Matillion ETL here: 

<https://www.matillion.com/etl-for-snowflake/>
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec340}See also {#see-also .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   There are couple more great features of Snowflake that can be handy
    for Tableau users. The first one is [**Snowflake Time
    Travel**]{.strong}. Imagine the[]{#id325272516 .indexterm} situation
    where your business dashboard gives your wrong metrics, but you feel
    that yesterday or last week the numbers were different? There is no
    way to check this. However, with the Time Travel feature we can
    easily query tables from the[]{#id325272524 .indexterm} past. You
    can adjust the existing data source with custom SQL and travel back
    in time. You can learn more
    here <https://docs.snowflake.net/manuals/user-guide/data-time-travel.html>
-   The second feature is [**Snowflake Data Sharing**]{.strong}. This
    feature[]{#id325285828 .indexterm} allows us to enable data
    consumers with access read-only copies of live data that\'s in a
    data provider account. You can think about creating a virtual copy
    of a database with special permissions. You can[]{#id325285836
    .indexterm} learn more here:
    <https://docs.snowflake.net/manuals/user-guide-data-share.html>



[]{#ch10lvl1sec103}Connecting Amazon Elastic MapReduce with Apache Hive {#connecting-amazon-elastic-mapreduce-with-apache-hive .title style="clear: both"}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

[**Amazon Elastic MapReduce**]{.strong} ([**EMR**]{.strong}) is a true
big data[]{#id325194984 .indexterm} platform. It provides[]{#id325194976
.indexterm} a managed Hadoop framework that can process a huge volume of
data across dynamically scalable Amazon EC2 instances. It allows us to
run popular distributed frameworks with it, such as Presto, Hive, Spark,
and others. This is a short[]{#id325194967 .indexterm} video about
Amazon EMR: <https://youtu.be/S6Ja55n-o0M>.

 

 Organizations use Hadoop for big data use cases, such as clickstream
analysis, log analysis, predictive analytics, data transformation, data
lake, and many more. Often, business users need to work with raw data
that is stored in Hadoop, in our case Amazon EMR. There are multiple
ways to connect Hadoop with Tableau, such as Presto, Hive, and more.

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec341}Getting ready {#getting-ready .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

We should launch the cluster, get sample data, and connect it via
Tableau Desktop using Hive. Let\'s do this! But be aware, EMR cluster
isn\'t free and you might spend \$20-\$30 in order go through scenarios.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec342}How to do it\... {#how-to-do-it... .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

Let\'s create our EMR cluster.

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  Go to the AWS account: <https://aws.amazon.com/console/> and sign
    in.
2.  Follow the instructions[]{#id325192708 .indexterm} present
    here: <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/emr/latest/ManagementGuide/emr-gs.html>
    in order to launch a cluster. You should perform the following three
    steps first:
    ::: {.orderedlist}
    a.  Set up prerequisites
    b.  Launch the cluster
    c.  Allow SSH access
    :::
:::

We used the following names:

::: {.informaltable}
  ----------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  [**Bucket name**]{.strong}          `tableau_cookbook`{.literal}
  [**Folder name**]{.strong}          `tableau-cookbook-query-result`{.literal}
  [**Key pair name**]{.strong}        `tableau-cookbook.pem`{.literal}
  [**Cluster name**]{.strong}         `My Cluster for Tableau Cookbook`{.literal}
  [**Cluster parameters**]{.strong}   `Core Hadoop: Hadoop 2.8.4 with Ganglia 3.7.2, Hive 2.3.3, Hue 4.2.0, Mahout 0.13.0, Pig 0.17.0, and Tez 0.8.4`{.literal}
  ----------------------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

 

As a result, we should be able to successfully launch the EMR cluster.
In addition, we can connect our cluster via SSH using the
`tableau-cookbook.pem`{.literal} key.

::: {.orderedlist}
4.  Let\'s connect[]{#id325192627 .indexterm} the cluster by running the
    following command:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
ssh -i ~/.ssh/tableua-cookbook.pem hadoop@ec2-18-215-157-216.compute-1.amazonaws.com
```
:::

::: {.note style="margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;"}
### []{#note34}Note {#note .title}

I saved my key in the `.ssh`{.literal} folder and the key should have
400 permissions.
:::

In the following screenshot we can see the following output:

::: {.mediaobject}
![](17_files/a551bbb6-8b79-4747-a75f-266a05b40e1e.png)
:::
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec343}How it works\... {#how-it-works... .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

Using AWS, we launched[]{#id325272509 .indexterm} EMR cluster. In
addition, we accessed it with SSH using[]{#id325272518 .indexterm} key.
You can learn more about EMR in AWS
documantation: <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/emr/latest/ManagementGuide/emr-gs.html>

 


[]{#ch10lvl1sec104}Creating sample data {#creating-sample-data .title style="clear: both"}
---------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

Next, we want to create a Hive external[]{#id325272442 .indexterm} table
on top of S3 logs and use EMR to compute the results. We can do this
using the following three different methods:

::: {.itemizedlist}
-   Using EMR CLI
-   Using EMR console
-   Using web GUI
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec344}How to do it\... {#how-to-do-it... .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

It depends on your preferences. In my example, I will use EMR CLI. We
should already be connected to the EMR cluster via SSH. Let\'s start to
work with Hive:

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  In EMR CLI type `hive`{.literal} and it will launch Hive.
2.  Next, we can execute SQL commands. Let\'s create the table on top of
    the CloudFront logs that are stored in the S3 bucket. We will run
    this DDL, as follows:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
hive>CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE IF NOT EXISTS cloudfront_logs (
  DateObject Date,
  Time STRING,
  Location STRING,
  Bytes INT,
  RequestIP STRING,
  Method STRING,
  Host STRING,
  Uri STRING,
  Status INT,
  Referrer STRING,
  OS String,
  Browser String, 
  BrowserVersion String
)
ROW FORMAT SERDE 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.serde2.RegexSerDe'
WITH SERDEPROPERTIES (
  "input.regex" = "^(?!#)([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+([^ ]+)\\s+[^\(]+[\(]([^\;]+).*\%20([^\/]+)[\/](.*)$"
) LOCATION 's3://us-east-1.elasticmapreduce.samples/cloudfront/data';
```
:::

 

 

::: {.note style="margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;"}
### []{#note35}Note {#note .title}

It is important that region location is in the same region as where we
have the EMR cluster, that is in my case it is `us-east-1`{.literal}.
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
3.  We can test our new table, by running[]{#id325185445 .indexterm} the
    following simple query:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
Hive>SELECT os, COUNT(*) count FROM cloudfront_logs GROUP BY os;
```
:::

Let\'s look at the results in the following screenshot:

::: {.mediaobject}
![](18_files/df684c99-f14a-4b05-be61-d9c16edde8e6.png)
:::

You can see that the query works. Despite the fact that it has a fairly
small amount of data, the query took 32 seconds. This is how Hadoop
works, it takes a long time for initialization and other complementary
steps. This is true for any big data system and should work for big
data. You can also experiment with other SQL-friendly Hadoop tools, such
as Impala, Presto, and so on. For us, the main feature of these guys is
their connection to the Tableau via the ODBC driver.

 

::: {.orderedlist}
4.  Let\'s create one more table, using the [*Google Books
    N-grams*]{.emphasis} dataset. It is an AWS public dataset available
    for everyone. You can read more[]{#id324855909 .indexterm} about it
    here: <https://registry.opendata.aws/google-ngrams/>. Let\'s create
    the Hive table[]{#id324944089 .indexterm} for 1-gram, as follows:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
hive> CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE eng_1M_1gram(token STRING, year INT, frequency INT, pages   
 INT, books INT) ROW FORMAT DELIMITED FIELDS TERMINATED BY 't' STORED AS SEQUENCEFILE   
  LOCATION 's3://datasets.elasticmapreduce/ngrams/books/20090715/eng-1M/1gram';
```
:::

As a result, we will get one more table. This table has 261,823,186
rows.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec345}How it works\... {#how-it-works... .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

We used Apache Hive that was deployed on top of an EMR cluster.  In
addition, we queried two datasets using Hive SQL.
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec346}There's more... {#theres-more .title}

</div>

:::

[]{#ch10lvl1sec105}Connect Tableau with  Apache Hive {#connect-tableau-with-apache-hive .title style="clear: both"}
----------------------------------------------------

</div>

</div>

------------------------------------------------------------------------
:::

The fastest way to connect[]{#id325189362 .indexterm} Tableau to AWS EMR
via Hive JDBC is to open[]{#id325185465 .indexterm} an SSH tunnel to the
master node. Let\'s connect.

 

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec348}How to do it... {#how-to-do-it .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

::: {.orderedlist}
1.  Open Terminal and run the following command:
:::

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.programlisting .language-markup}
ssh -o ServerAliveInterval=10 -i ~/.ssh/tableau-cookbook.pem -N -L 10000:localhost:10000 hadoop@ec2-18-215-157-216.compute-1.amazonaws.com
```
:::

But this could be a different command in your case.

::: {.orderedlist}
2.  Open Tableau Desktop and create a new connection using Amazon Hadoop
    EMR Hive.

3.  Download and install ODBC drivers for your[]{#id324934010
    .indexterm} OS
    from:<https://docs.aws.amazon.com/emr/latest/ManagementGuide/emr-bi-tools.html>

4.  Now, we can connect Hive, as follows:
:::

::: {.mediaobject}
![](19_files/9a9c3e83-da53-47a2-84e4-6acaddd69a17.png)
:::

 

::: {.orderedlist}
5.  Then choose **`default`** as a schema and **`cloudfront_logs`** as a
    table and go to the sheet. As you know, every drag and drop will
    initialize[]{#id324934025 .indexterm} the SQL query
    and[]{#id325192635 .indexterm} will trigger our EMR. In order to
    avoid this, we should pause Auto Updates and create our report, then
    run the final query, as follows:
:::

::: {.mediaobject}
![](19_files/9be80f01-edd8-4e0e-bf6c-e2b40564c8e1.png)

As a result, we were able to connect to Tableau. You can connect to the
bigger `eng_1M_1gram`{.literal} table as well. There are lots of
different techniques for accessing data from Hadoop, and often it
depends on use case.
:::

::: {.titlepage}

### []{#ch10lvl2sec349}How it works... {#how-it-works .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

In our scenario, we connected Tableau Desktop to EMR cluster via Apache
Hive. As usual, we left all the heavy work to ERM cluster and used
Apache Hive in order to get an SQL interface to the Hadoop cluster. 

 
:::

::: {.section lang="en" lang="en"}
::: {.titlepage}
<div>

<div>

### []{#ch10lvl2sec350}There\'s more... {#theres-more .title}

</div>

</div>
:::

 You can also use Impala. It is also an open-source tool in the Hadoop
ecosystem. Instead of using MapReduce, as Hive does, it is using MPP
(similar to the analytical data warehouse), which gives us a better
query performance but requires additional[]{#id325192715 .indexterm}
steps. Hive and[]{#id325192724 .indexterm} Impala both use Hive
Metastore, but Hive requires more time to process the query and it isn't
very efficient for improvised analyses. Impala requires data to be
stored on HDFS. Moreover, it depends on the memory resource of clusters.
As a result, every tool has its own pros and[]{#id325194923 .indexterm}
cons. You can read more here:

<https://vision.cloudera.com/impala-v-hive/>
:::
